The whole of the foregoing review of the philosophy of the ancients is drawn to a close by an examination into the Ideal Hypothesis of Plato.
The inconsistencies of this hypothesis are unsparingly exposed;
the very arguments brought forward by its advocates in its favour are in reality subversive of it;
it is quite insufficient to ac­ count for actual phenomena;
it brings nothing forward that can advance the interests of science;
and therefore for each and all of these reasons is by no means to be received with unhesitating assent.
