In the two remaining chapters of the tenth book there is not to be found anything that can be considered important, when compared with what has gone before, and is about to follow in book XI.
They are both occupied with the subject of motion in relation to change.
There are three changes, either from a subject into a subject, or from a non-subject into a subject, or from a subject into a non-subject:
