and Anaxagoras, in his system of the infinity of homogeneous things.
Now, truly, all these touched upon a cause of this kind:
and, further, as many as affirmed the existence, as a first principle, of air, or fire, or water, or a substance of greater density than fire, but of greater rarity than air;
for certain philosophers have also declared a thing of this sort to be the first element.
All these, indeed, there­ fore, adopted this cause merely in a superficial way.
But certain others introduce the second cause;
namely, the origin of the principle of motion:
as, for instance, as many as make a first principle of harmony and discord, or mind or love.
