But, doubtless, if any one makes a supposition in this way, so that, as some say, from actual unity, and a something else that is not one, is com­ posed number, not the less should it form a subject for investigation, why, and how, what is produced will one time be number, and another time, magnitude, if what is not one be inequality and the same nature.
For neither is it mani­ fest how from one and this natnre, nor how from a certain number and this nature, magnitudes would arise.
BUT a doubt connected with these is, whether numbers and bodies, and surfaces and points, are certain substances or not ?
For if they are not, it eludes our comprehension what being 1.
