stances t is, and what the substances of entities are.
For passive pro­ perties, and motions, and relations, and dispositions, and ratios, do not appear to signify a substance of anything;
for all these are predicated respecting a certain subject, and no one of them can be said to be this or that particular thing.
But things which would seem particularly to signify sub­ stance, namely, water, and earth, and fire, from which compounded bodies consist, the heats and colds of these and such like qualities are affections, not substances;
but all the while the body, which undergoes these passive conditions, alone sustains them as a certain entity, and as being a certain substance.
But, truly, both body is less substance than a superficies, and this latter than a line, and this than the monad and the point, for by these is body defined.
And these, indeed, seem capable of existence with­ out body;
but the existence of body, without these, seems impossible.
Wherefore, the majority of speculators and our predecessors considered substance and entity to be body, and the other things to be passive 2.
