and the other things now are termed essentially perfect in respect either of the doing some such thing, or the having it in possession, or of the adaptation of itself to this,1 or in accordance, at least, with some other mode of expression in relation to things that are primarily called perfectA TERMINATION is called the last of each thing, and beyond which, as first, it is not possible to assume anything, and within which, as first, are comprised all things, and that, likewise, which 1.
