For there is a certain cause of health, and of a good habit of body, and of mathematical entities;
likewise are there first principles, and elements, and causes;
and in general, also, every science which is an intellectual one, or in any degree even partaking of the faculty of thought,2 is con­ versant about causes and first principles, which are either more accurate or more simple, as the case may be.
All of these, however, being descriptive of one particular subject, and a particular genus, are engaged about this;
