But the name, energy,1 which is combined with actuality, and tends towards other things, has proceeded forth from motions principally;
for motion in an eminent sense appears to constitute the energy of a thing.
Wherefore, also, to nonentities they do not attribute the having motion imparted to them, but certain other categories:
as, for instance, things which are nonentities are intelligible and desirable objects, but are not in motion.
And this is the case because nonentities in energy will, how­ ever, subsist in energy;
