But the inquiry as to the nature of any­ thing is being instituted by us in respect of these natures, as to whether there are things of this sort at all, or not;
and the fact is, the existence of a thing is as that which is true, and its non-existence as that which is false;
in one way, if it is that which is compounded, it is true, whereas, in the other, if it is not a composite nature, it is false:
and in another way, if we suppose it to exist in this way, it is true, but if not in this way, it is not true.
