for it seems, certainly, to constitute the most divine existence amongst phenomena:
but after what manner it is disposed, so as that it should be a thing of this sort, is attended with certain difficulties.
For whether it be void of the faculty of understanding anything, but is like one who is sleeping, what, may I ask, would there be reverential in such a con­ dition of being ?
Or, supposing that it possesses the faculty of understanding, and yet that there be something which is dominant over this faculty-for in this case that which is its substance is not intelligence, but capacity-should the fore­ going be true, we could not say that Mind would be the most excellent substance ;
for it is through the faculty of the under­ standing that that which is entitled to reverence is inherent in the mind.
